english:
  title: Inscription for the Hall of Twin Plums, with Preface
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A name must correspond to reality. When a name no longer fits what it names, it may be changed.

    Once I built a hall to the west of my residence. Two pine trees grew there, so I named it the Hall of Twin Pines. My friend from my examination year, Lee Ji-jung, wrote an account of it. After serving in the capital for several years, I returned to find the pines had fallen, leaving only two plum trees standing. I immediately changed the hall's name to the Hall of Twin Plums. At first I named it for what existed—the pines—but what I named disappeared, so I renamed it for what now exists—the plums. What fault is there in this? Since I name things by what lies before my eyes, naming and renaming are easily done. In ancient times, Tao Yuanming had five willows by his cottage and took the name Five Willows Recluse—a matter of chance. My naming of this hall is much the same. Though the name has changed, the hall itself gains nothing and loses nothing.

    The inscription reads:

    Two plum trees stand paired,
    their roots fixed in this hall.
    Branch upon branch gleams jade,
    early sensing spring's warmth.
    Snow and frost cannot veil
    their fragrance.
    Clothed in unswerving virtue,
    they match the steadfastness of Bo Yi.
    Not for idle viewing—
    love them with reverence.
    Would you doubt my words?
    See truth written here in stone.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Bo Yi (伯夷) was an ancient sage known for his moral integrity and refusal to compromise his principles, making him a traditional symbol of virtue in Chinese literature.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Tao Yuanming (陶淵明), the celebrated recluse poet of the Jin Dynasty, invokes the tradition of literati naming their dwellings after natural features present on their land.
  - key: ''
    value: The changing of names from Twin Pines to Twin Plums reflects not fickleness but philosophical acceptance of impermanence and the wisdom of adapting to circumstance while maintaining inner constancy.
